            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

        <td>song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>A Fox Sparrow singing from a dense and extensive patch of shrubby cinquefoil at Brainard Lake. Cool with very light rain.</p>

<p>bird-seen:no</p>

                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Alarm calls by sooty fox sparrows in response to playback of a northern pygmy owl recording.</p>

<p>Recorded in montane chaparral on a west-facing slope near the edge of open forest with bigcone Douglas-fir, canyon and interior live oak, California bay, and incense cedar.</p>

<p>Equipment: Sony PCM-M10 recorder and a Sennheiser MKE-400 microphone.
Edits to the file: None.</p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

        <a href='/contributor/MDZVOPUOXU'>Lance A. M. Benner</a>

        <td>2016-10-30</td>
        <td> 10:44</td>
      
        <td>United States</td>
        <td>
          <a href="/location/map?lat=34.2169&long=-117.6931&loc=Sunset+Peak+lower+saddle%2C+Los+Angeles+County%2C+California">Sunset Peak lower saddle, Los Angeles County, California</a>
        </td>
        <td>1600</td>
        <td>alarm call </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Alarm calls by sooty fox sparrows in response to playback of a northern pygmy owl recording.</p>

<p>Recorded in montane chaparral on a west-facing slope near the edge of open forest with bigcone Douglas-fir, canyon and interior live oak, California bay, and incense cedar.</p>

<p>Equipment: Sony PCM-M10 recorder and a Sennheiser MKE-400 microphone.
Edits to the file: none.</p>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

        <td>90</td>
        <td>flight call </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Natural vocalization. High flight call at <a onclick='xc.playFrom(291257, 0);'>0:00</a>, <a onclick='xc.playFrom(291257, 10);'>0:10</a>, and <a onclick='xc.playFrom(291257, 28);'>0:28</a>. This bird flushed from the tall grass on my approach and perched in a 1.5m tall locust sapling where it called several times before flying away. Distance from microphone ~5m.</p>

<h1>Habitat</h1>

<p>State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.</p>

<h1>Editing</h1>

<p>Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff <em>4 kHz</em>, order 3</p>

<h1>Equipment</h1>

<p>Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.</p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>lone bird just off the ground in the burnt forest, no calls missed from beginning to end</p>

                                   <ul class='jp-controls'>
                                     <li><a href='javascript:;' class='jp-play' tabindex='1'>play</a></li> 
                                     <li><a href='javascript:;' class='jp-pause' style='display:none;' tabindex='1'>pause</a></li>

                       </div>
                   </div>
               </div>
           </div></td>
        <td>
        <span class='common-name'><a href='/species/Passerella-iliaca'>Fox Sparrow</a></span> (<span class='scientific-name'>Passerella iliaca chilcatensis</span>)
        </td>
        <td>
        3:30
        </td>
        <td>
        <a href='/contributor/KZYUWIRZVH'>Richard E. Webster</a>
        </td>
        
        <td>2014-06-23</td>
        <td> 14:08</td>
      
        <td>United States</td>
        <td>
          <a href="/location/map?lat=55.9646&long=-130.0618&loc=Fish+Creek%2C+near+Hyder%2C+Alaska">Fish Creek, near Hyder, Alaska</a>
        </td>
        <td>40</td>
        <td>song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>This is a "Sooty" Fox Sparrow, the subspecies a recently-described one (different Webster, no relation!), for "onshore" fuliginosa that had been noted as different from fuliginosa at least starting with Swarth.  Of more interest, the localities at which we saw and recorded chilcatensis are only 20-30 km from the Salmon Glacier locality (from which Andrew Spencer also has records) for what I am calling altivagans, of the  "Slate-colored" group.   The birds differ in plumage, habitat (chilcatensis is in thickets in wet, lowland sites, altivagans in subalpine or treeline stunted conifers, about 800m in elevation as a gap, although my coverage of that transect was brief and I don't know the limits of either), and somewhat in song.  [Webster, J.D. Proc. Biol. Soc. Wash. 1983 for chilcatensis]; 3rd recording of this individual, per ann., "delayed RPB", but not sure how long (I photographed between 2nd and 3rd cuts) the delay was; using a call note and an interesting buzz as intros, and a chup similar to the altivagans up the mountain as a final note;</p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

<p>playback-used:yes</p>

        <td>Canada</td>
        <td>
          <a href="/location/map?lat=56.1&long=-130.0452&loc=Salmon+Glacier%2C+Stewart%2C+British+Columbia">Salmon Glacier, Stewart, British Columbia</a>
        </td>
        <td>1000</td>
        <td>song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Subspecies ID based on descriptions in Swarth and Unitt and on observed differences with lowland birds nearby; birds from this area may show some approach to Sooty types, but are still clearly largely different in plumage.   While I did not use altivagans for recordings in the Rockies, where birds look quite different and much more like schistacea to me (but see discussion started by Andrew Spencer regarding Jasper N.P. recordings), those locales are most often included in altivagans, the problem being that, as Swarth noted (UC Pub  Zoo 21: 124) "It is quite possible that the name altivagans as now used covers a composite of several recognizable subspecies . . . ."   </p>

<p>1st recording of this individual, in treeline stunted spruce; </p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

<p>playback-used:no</p>

        <td>
        <span class='common-name'><a href='/species/Passerella-iliaca'>Fox Sparrow</a></span> (<span class='scientific-name'>Passerella iliaca schistacea</span>)
        </td>
        <td>
        2:25
        </td>
        <td>
        <a href='/contributor/KZYUWIRZVH'>Richard E. Webster</a>
        </td>
        
        <td>2014-06-21</td>
        <td> 10:37</td>
      
        <td>Canada</td>
        <td>
          <a href="/location/map?lat=55.4206&long=-123.0454&loc=Morfee+Mountain%2C+near+Mackenzie%2C+British+Columbia">Morfee Mountain, near Mackenzie, British Columbia</a>
        </td>
        <td>1200</td>
        <td>song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Individual No 7 recorded here today; regarding the subspecies, the birds here look like the birds farther south in the Rockies (see forum started by Andrew Spencer re Jasper N.P. records), which is like schistacea in comparison to altivagans, particularly in the extensive gray on the head and some on the back, and unlike altivagans as generally characterized by many (Swarth, modern birder lit).   Both are (largely) genetically Slate-colored (Zink et al.); singing from the top of a tall spruce</p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

<p>playback-used:no</p>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

          <a href="/location/map?lat=52.2189&long=-117.1738&loc=Wilcox+Creek+Campground%2C+Jasper+National+Park%2C+Alberta">Wilcox Creek Campground, Jasper National Park, Alberta</a>
        </td>
        <td>2100</td>
        <td>call, song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>natural vocalization; quiet calls and song (together comprising excited song) from a bird counter-singing with a far away individual.  Habitat was a dense willow carr mixed with a few spruce trees, surrounded by tall coniferous forest not far below treeline.  This is a different bird than the one on <a href='/187647'>XC187647</a>.  Subspecies ID based on plumage as well as location.</p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;

    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            
            <table id='map-table'>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

        <a href='/contributor/CDTGHVBGZP'>Andrew Spencer</a>

        <td>United States</td>
        <td>
          <a href="/location/map?lat=48.9552&long=-117.068&loc=Salmo+Divide+Trail%2C+Colville+National+Forest%2C+Pend+Oreille+Co.%2C+Washington">Salmo Divide Trail, Colville National Forest, Pend Oreille Co., Washington</a>
        </td>
        <td>1800</td>
        <td>call, flight call </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>natural vocalizations; flight calls from a bird (a different one than in <a href='/110385'>XC110385</a> and <a href='/110386'>XC110386</a>), perched low in dense undergrowth of spruce-fir forest. These birds looked to me to be from the Slate-colored (schistacea) group, but these calls seem to fall closer to the Sooty (unalaschcensis) group. All of the birds I saw and recorded in this area appeared to me to be Slate-colored birds, but called like this bird, except for one bird that looked to me to be an altivagans individual.</p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

<p>playback-used:no</p>

All of the birds I saw and recorded in this area appeared to me to be Slate-colored birds, but called like this bird, except for one bird that looked to me to be an altivagans individual.</p>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

    }

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

        <span class='common-name'><a href='/species/Passerella-iliaca'>Fox Sparrow</a></span> (<span class='scientific-name'>Passerella iliaca</span>)

        <td>
        0:47
        </td>
        <td>
        <a href='/contributor/LFHJNCJRID'>Skip Russell</a>
        </td>
        
        <td>2016-06-04</td>
        <td> 16:41</td>
      
        <td>United States</td>
        <td>
          <a href="/location/map?lat=45.5739&long=-121.5867&loc=Hood+River%2C+Hood+River+County%2C+Oregon">Hood River, Hood River County, Oregon</a>
        </td>
        <td>650</td>
        <td>call, song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Two sharp chips, followed by a series of songs (<a onclick='xc.playFrom(320184, 11);'>0:11</a>).  The subject bird was likely attending a nest.  This same pattern of chips followed by songs repeated a few times over the course of an hour before I was able to catch it on a recording.  Most likely Slate-colored Fox Sparrow (schistacea group).  At the time, I thought I might be hearing one of the "Thick-billed" Fox Sparrow subspecies.  I would have liked to have gotten visual confirmation of what I recorded, as these and Green-tailed Towhee can sometimes sound similar, but the bird was in an inaccessible wet thicket and I was unable.  I made a followup visit to the same location two weeks later, but by then the birds were nowhere to be found.  I believe Fox Sparrow to be much more likely than Green-tailed Towhee at that particular spot given the habitat.</p>

<p>I made this recording using my Samsung S4 phone.  I removed approximately 4 seconds of audio after the chip notes and before the first song, leaving the interval between songs otherwise unaltered.
I amplified the song portion, but left the chip notes unamplified to avoid clipping.</p>

<p>bird-seen:no</p>

<p>playback-used:no</p>

        <td>song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Natural sound.</p>

<h1>Habitat</h1>

<p>State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.</p>

<h1>Editing</h1>

<p>No edits.</p>

<h1>Equipment</h1>

<p>Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector. </p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

<p>playback-used:no</p>

                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Natural sound.</p>

<h1>Habitat</h1>

<p>State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.</p>

<h1>Editing</h1>

<p>No edits.</p>

<h1>Equipment</h1>

<p>Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector. </p>

<h1>Habitat</h1>

<p>State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.</p>

<p>No edits.</p>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>This short recording documents a couple dozen calls of a Fox Sparrow (Sooty) as it hopped around the vegetation a couple of meters from me.</p>

<p>More details of the context of this recording may be found here: <a href="http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S25507224">http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S25507224</a></p>

<p>This recording was made with an iPhone 5s with a Sennheiser mic and Rde Rec application. This is an unedited and unmodified recording of the natural spacing of these birds' utterances.</p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

        <td>song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>This 28-second recording documents 3 songs of an adult male Fox Sparrow (Thick-billed). A review of the range map in The Distribution of the Bird of California (Grinnell and Miller, 1944) shows that the locale of this recording is within the range of <em>Passerella iliaca megarhyncha</em>.</p>

<p>This recording was made with an iPhone 5s with Sennheiser microphone and Rde Rec application. This recording has not been modified or edited.</p>

<p>Additional details and context may be found at: <a href="http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S23917299">http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S23917299</a></p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

I failed to find a recording to match this song. I assumed it was a warbler, but checked some other species to no avail. I filtered out some lower and higher frequency background sound/noise. This was recorded using the video of a Canon 7D DSLR.</p>

<p>This was identified as a Fox Sparrow, which winter in our area, and don't usually sing during this time.</p>

           </div></td>
        <td>
        <span class='common-name'><a href='/species/Passerella-iliaca'>Fox Sparrow</a></span> (<span class='scientific-name'>Passerella iliaca chilcatensis</span>)
        </td>
        <td>
        0:54
        </td>
        <td>
        <a href='/contributor/KZYUWIRZVH'>Richard E. Webster</a>
        </td>
        
        <td>2014-06-23</td>
        <td> 13:31</td>
      
        <td>United States</td>
        <td>
          <a href="/location/map?lat=55.9646&long=-130.0618&loc=Fish+Creek%2C+near+Hyder%2C+Alaska">Fish Creek, near Hyder, Alaska</a>
        </td>
        <td>40</td>
        <td>song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>This is a "Sooty" Fox Sparrow, the subspecies a recently-described one (different Webster, no relation!), for "onshore" fuliginosa that had been noted as different from fuliginosa at least starting with Swarth.  Of more interest, the localities at which we saw and recorded chilcatensis are only 20-30 km from the Salmon Glacier locality (from which Andrew Spencer also has records) for what I am calling altivagans, of the  "Slate-colored" group.   The birds differ in plumage, habitat (chilcatensis is in thickets in wet, lowland sites, altivagans in subalpine or treeline stunted conifers, about 800m in elevation as a gap, although my coverage of that transect was brief and I don't know the limits of either), and somewhat in song.  [Webster, J.D. Proc. Biol. Soc. Wash. 1983 for chilcatensis]</p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

<p>playback-used:no</p>

        <td>Canada</td>
        <td>
          <a href="/location/map?lat=55.4206&long=-123.0454&loc=Morfee+Mountain%2C+near+Mackenzie%2C+British+Columbia">Morfee Mountain, near Mackenzie, British Columbia</a>
        </td>
        <td>1400</td>
        <td>song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Individual No 6 recorded here today; regarding the subspecies, the birds here look like the birds farther south in the Rockies (see forum started by Andrew Spencer re Jasper N.P. records), which is like schistacea in comparison to altivagans, particularly in the extensive gray on the head and some on the back, and unlike altivagans as generally characterized by many (Swarth, modern birder lit).   Both are (largely) genetically Slate-colored (Zink et al.); short songs followed by full versions; short spruce near treeline</p>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Calls by a Sooty Fox Sparrow.</p>

                   <div id='xc_audio_161407_763' class='jp-type-single' data-xc-id='161407' data-xc-filepath='http://www.xeno-canto.org/sounds/uploaded/UYFSBFJOXQ/XC161407-Recording%205a-Fox%20Sparrow.mp3'>

        <td>
        <span class='common-name'><a href='/species/Passerella-iliaca'>Fox Sparrow</a></span> (<span class='scientific-name'>Passerella iliaca</span>)
        </td>
        <td>
        0:54
        </td>
        <td>
        <a href='/contributor/UYFSBFJOXQ'>L G Price</a>
        </td>
        
        <td>2013-12-28</td>
        <td> 10:00</td>
      
        <td>United States</td>
        <td>
          <a href="/location/map?lat=32.6363&long=-94.7843&loc=Bethlehem%2C+Upshur%2C+Texas">Bethlehem, Upshur, Texas</a>
        </td>
        <td>100</td>
        <td>call, smack call, song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>There were 6-8 Fox Sparrows in the small hollow near the road. I played an eastern Fox Sparrow Song and Smack calls using the Sibley app on my iPhone to see if I could get them to vocalize. I heard two give songs, although the recording is of only one singing. Also heard are others making the Smack call.</p>

<p>recorded made with an iPhone and Blue Fire software. I edited using Audacity and applied a 400 Hz High Pass Filter at 12 dB followed by a 600 Hz High Pass Filter at 6 dB.</p>

<p>bird-seen:yes</p>

<p>playback-used:yes</p>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

<script type='text/javascript'>
function showSpeciesNr(value, data)
{
    jQuery('#species_nr').val(data.species_nr);
    jQuery('#quick-search-bar > form').submit();
    }
    </script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            
            <table id='map-table'>
            <tr>

            <div id='map-canvas'></div>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};

    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            
            <table id='map-table'>
            <tr>

                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Slate-colored fox sparrow.  Heard and seen in response to playback of a mountain quail recording.</p>

<p>Recorded in open chaparral, dominated by chamise, in an area that burned extensively in September 2009.</p>

<p>Equipment: Sony PCM-M10, Sennheiser ME62, and a 22 inch Telinga dish.
Edits to the file: trimmed.</p>

<p>Sounds of two flying insects bouncing off the dish are also audible.</p>

        0:06
        </td>
        <td>
        <a href='/contributor/RSRUUVOCGA'>J.R. Rigby</a>
        </td>
        
        <td>2015-11-19</td>
        <td> 08:00</td>
      
        <td>United States</td>
        <td>
          <a href="/location/map?lat=34.4842&long=-89.5949&loc=Oxford%2C+Lafayette+County%2C+Mississippi">Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi</a>
        </td>
        <td>90</td>
        <td>call, song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Natural vocalization. Singing from within dense ground cover, mostly grasses and partridgepea one to two meters in height. There seems to have been an influx of Fox Sparrows with a weather front that brought ~5" of rain two days ago, with several FOSP singing in close proximity on this morning. Distance from microphone ~5m.</p>

<h1>Habitat</h1>

<p>State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.</p>

<h1>Editing</h1>

<p>Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff 700 hz, order 3</p>

<h1>Equipment</h1>

<p>Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.</p>

<p>bird-seen:no</p>

<p>playback-used:no</p>

                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>This bird was singing from a dense stand of shrubby willow in a narrow riparian corridor with a small stream flowing through a fairly steep sided gorge with an adjacent stand of Aspen on one side and Pinyon-Juniper on the other.  At the end of each song phrase the bird does a spot on impression of two different common American Robin calls, alternating the calls with each song phrase.  It was probably about 10-15ft from me and about 5 ft off the ground. </p>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

</script>

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});

            <h1>Fox Sparrow &middot; <span class='sci-name'>Passerella iliaca</span> &middot; <span class='authority'>(Merrem, 1786)</span></h1>
            
            <ul class='taxonomy order'>
            <li>Order: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?o=PASSERIFORMES'>PASSERIFORMES</a>
            <ul class='family'>
            <li>Family: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?f=Emberizidae'>Emberizidae</a> (Buntings, New World Sparrows and allies)
            <ul class='genus'>
            <li>Genus: <a href='/explore/taxonomy?g=Passerella'>Passerella</a></li>
            <ul class='species'>
            <li>Species: <span class='sci-name'>iliaca</span></li>
            </ul>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>
            </li>
            </ul>

        <td>175</td>
        <td>Song </td>
          
                <td><div class='remarks readmore'><p>Rarely sings at this latitude just prior to migrating back north.</p>
<p>   </p></div> <span class="tooltip" data-qtip-header="Other Species"
            data-qtip-content="&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#039;/species/Agelaius-phoeniceus&#039;&gt;Red-winged Blackbird&lt;/a&gt; (Agelaius phoeniceus)&lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#039;/species/Spinus-tristis&#039;&gt;American Goldfinch&lt;/a&gt; (Spinus tristis)&lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;/ul&gt;" >[also]</span>
            <a class='fancybox' rel='sono' href='http://www.xeno-canto.org/sounds/uploaded/AZXTZTQJRO/ffts/XC16927-large.png' title='XC16927: Fox Sparrow (Passerella iliaca iliaca) by Allen T. Chartier'>[sono]</a></div></td>

xc.initMap = function()
{
    try {
        var map = xc.createMap("map-canvas", "http://www.xeno-canto.org/ranges/Passerella_iliaca.kmz?v=2", false);
        map.setMarkers(xc.initialMarkers.markers, xc.initialMarkers.specs, true);

        return map;
    } catch (e) {
        return null;
    }
};


var xcmap = null;
jQuery(document).ready(function() {
    xcmap = xc.initMap();
});
